00:34:47.409 --> 00:34:49.702
So he would come in from time
to time and we would do

00:34:49.702 --> 00:34:50.539
different things.
 

00:34:50.539 --> 00:34:54.849
So Lauren, as I've mentioned,
is a very experienced singer,

00:34:54.849 --> 00:34:57.202
and we're going to do a little
aria here out of Mozart's

00:34:57.202 --> 00:34:58.905
Figaro,
his opera The Marriage of

00:34:58.905 --> 00:35:01.076
Figaro,
1786, called "Voi che

00:35:01.076 --> 00:35:02.000
sapete."
 

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:06.469
So Lauren, can you tell us
something about this aria?

00:35:06.469 --> 00:35:08.000
Who's singing it?
 

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:11.445
Student:  This aria is
sung by Cherubino,

00:35:11.445 --> 00:35:14.744
who is a young boy,
actuallyâ€“I'm wearing

00:35:14.744 --> 00:35:16.650
pants for the purpose.
 

00:35:16.650 --> 00:35:20.260
It's called a "trouser
role" for that reason.

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:23.449
It's sung by a woman.
 

00:35:23.449 --> 00:35:25.900
Prof: Why do they do
that?

00:35:25.900 --> 00:35:32.630
Did the weird opera people like
transvestites or something?

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:36.914
There are other roles like
this--it's just kind a

00:35:36.914 --> 00:35:38.880
convention in opera.
 

00:35:38.880 --> 00:35:43.010
Student:  He is a young
boy--so maybe the high voice--

00:35:43.010 --> 00:35:45.327
Prof: He's an
adolescent, fourteen,

00:35:45.327 --> 00:35:47.250
and what's he experiencing
here?

00:35:47.250 --> 00:35:50.340
Student:  First love or
first lust.

00:35:50.340 --> 00:35:52.510
Prof: He's not sure.
 

00:35:52.510 --> 00:35:53.869
Student:  He's not sure.
 

00:35:53.869 --> 00:35:59.336
He's singing to the Countess,
with whom he's in love--with a

00:35:59.336 --> 00:36:01.840
little help from Susanna.
 

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:04.190
Prof: Susanna?
 

00:36:04.190 --> 00:36:05.980
So he thinks he's in love with
the countess,

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:07.896
but maybe it's Susanna or maybe
it's Barbarina,

00:36:07.896 --> 00:36:09.768
or maybe it's that broomstick
over there.

00:36:09.768 --> 00:36:12.987
It's really hard to know
exactly whom he's in love with

00:36:12.987 --> 00:36:14.059
at age fourteen.
 

00:36:14.059 --> 00:36:17.909
That's the confusion here.
 

00:36:17.909 --> 00:36:20.590
So if there's a certain
palpitation from time to time,

00:36:20.590 --> 00:36:24.018
it's intentional here--and a
certain sense of being

00:36:24.018 --> 00:36:25.927
flustered,
almost--agitated or

00:36:25.927 --> 00:36:28.980
flustered--you're uncertain
about what these things are.

00:36:28.980 --> 00:36:32.460
We're going to have Lauren sing
all of this for us.

00:36:32.460 --> 00:36:36.804
But in order to have this be
something other than just a

00:36:36.804 --> 00:36:41.385
performance, I'd like to work
through different pedagogical

00:36:41.385 --> 00:36:42.650
issues here.
 

00:36:42.650 --> 00:36:45.969
So let's talk about that just
for a second.

00:36:45.969 --> 00:36:48.802
Now, at the outset of this,
and you guys have your sheets

00:36:48.802 --> 00:36:50.965
out there;
there's a sheet on the music

00:36:50.965 --> 00:36:53.079
stand back there--you've got a
sheet.

00:36:53.079 --> 00:36:55.190
So take a look at that.
 

00:36:55.190 --> 00:37:00.429
And we'll see--what do you
see--Marcus?

00:37:00.429 --> 00:37:03.474
Right down here in the front
row, what do you see on your

00:37:03.474 --> 00:37:04.780
sheet by way of music?
 

00:37:04.780 --> 00:37:11.512
Student:  That it's
broken up into two different

00:37:11.512 --> 00:37:12.510
parts.
 

00:37:12.510 --> 00:37:13.269
Three, I guess.
 

00:37:13.269 --> 00:37:14.320
Prof: Three.
 

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:16.005
And they're labeled
"antecedent"

00:37:16.005 --> 00:37:17.199
and "consequent."
 

00:37:17.199 --> 00:37:20.445
So Mozart starts out here with
the antecedent and consequent

00:37:20.445 --> 00:37:21.489
phrase structure.
 

00:37:21.489 --> 00:37:29.630
&gt;
 

00:37:29.630 --> 00:37:31.809
That was the antecedent;
here comes consequent.

00:37:31.809 --> 00:37:37.460
&gt;
 

00:37:37.460 --> 00:37:39.530
So antecedent/consequent.
 

00:37:39.530 --> 00:37:43.166
Then, interestingly enough,
when the voice comes in,

00:37:43.166 --> 00:37:45.019
what does he do,
Lauren?

00:37:45.019 --> 00:37:46.610
What does he do there?
 

00:37:46.610 --> 00:37:49.489
You have to sing-- you just
don't duplicate what I did.

00:37:49.489 --> 00:37:53.360
Student:  He actually
expands different structure by

00:37:53.360 --> 00:37:55.829
adding more material in the
middle.

00:37:55.829 --> 00:37:57.429
Prof: So he had an A and
B,

00:37:57.429 --> 00:38:00.378
but his mind is such--I mean,
I'd never be able to figure

00:38:00.378 --> 00:38:02.068
that out--
he said, "Well,

00:38:02.068 --> 00:38:05.030
I can open this whole thing up
and put in some additional

00:38:05.030 --> 00:38:07.237
lovely music,
and then close it back down

00:38:07.237 --> 00:38:09.320
with my consequent phrase
structure."

00:38:09.320 --> 00:38:11.199
So we have that.
 

00:38:11.199 --> 00:38:12.670
Let's listen to how that plays
out.

00:38:12.670 --> 00:38:16.043
So we'll just start with where
you come in, Lauren,

00:38:16.043 --> 00:38:18.000
with "Voi,"
okay?

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:44.518
&lt;&lt;plays piano while
student sings&gt;&gt;

00:38:44.518 --> 00:38:47.960
And then we go on with a series
of phrases, and as you listen to

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:51.239
this, you might count the number
of bars and phrases here.

00:38:51.239 --> 00:38:54.025
But generally speaking,
they're all four bars in

00:38:54.025 --> 00:38:54.559
length.
 

00:38:54.559 --> 00:38:57.552
Mozart is one of the guys that
puts this whole idea of

00:38:57.552 --> 00:38:59.530
structure with melody on the
map.

00:38:59.530 --> 00:39:04.650
Structure, symmetry are very
important in his compositions.

00:39:04.650 --> 00:39:07.461
And as we proceed here,
the text gets more and more

00:39:07.461 --> 00:39:08.250
interesting.
 

00:39:08.250 --> 00:39:12.710
We start talking about feelings
at line five there.

00:39:12.710 --> 00:39:15.579
"Sento un
affetto"--how would you

00:39:15.579 --> 00:39:18.449
translate, I guess we have a
translator.

00:39:18.449 --> 00:39:19.670
Student:  "Sento un
affetto."

00:39:19.670 --> 00:39:21.324
"I feel,"--&amp;qu
ot;affetto"

00:39:21.324 --> 00:39:23.309
in Italian, that's like
"something."

00:39:23.309 --> 00:39:23.856
Prof: Emotion?
 

00:39:23.856 --> 00:39:24.429
Student:  Yes.
 

00:39:24.429 --> 00:39:27.923
Prof: And then sometimes
he is really happy,

00:39:27.923 --> 00:39:31.070
and then sometimes he's sort of
despairing.

00:39:31.070 --> 00:39:34.132
What's kind of cool,
when we get over to the

00:39:34.132 --> 00:39:37.478
despairing idea here on the
piano--&lt;&lt;plays

00:39:37.478 --> 00:39:38.690
piano&gt;&gt;
 

00:39:38.690 --> 00:39:44.809
We're here, and we go
to--&gt;

00:39:44.809 --> 00:39:49.880
And then he's going to be
burning like a flame and then

00:39:49.880 --> 00:39:54.295
freezing to death,
so we get the weird harmonies

00:39:54.295 --> 00:39:58.239
out here as he's freezing and
thawing.

00:39:58.239 --> 00:40:04.077
So let's hear just a little
bit, maybe with--from there--at

00:40:04.077 --> 00:40:07.699
"Sento un affetto"
okay?

00:40:07.699 --> 00:40:43.570
&lt;&lt;plays piano while
student sings&gt;&gt;

00:40:43.570 --> 00:40:44.320
Okay.
 

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:46.775
Now we're going to go on to a
little bit later--lovely,

00:40:46.775 --> 00:40:47.550
lovely, lovely.
 

00:40:47.550 --> 00:40:49.280
We're going to go on to a
little bit later.

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:53.793
If you can follow on your text
to "Sospiro e gemo senza

00:40:53.793 --> 00:40:57.849
voler, palpito e tremo senza
saper" and so on.

00:40:57.849 --> 00:41:02.518
What does Mozart do here in
terms of structure?

00:41:02.518 --> 00:41:08.054
Student:  A sequence He
repeats the same series of notes

00:41:08.054 --> 00:41:12.608
progressively higher,
to illustrate--as you hear the

00:41:12.608 --> 00:41:16.929
notes rising--angst--
Prof: Good. Agitation.

00:41:16.929 --> 00:41:21.789
So pick it up here at the
B-flat, and I'll try to catch

00:41:21.789 --> 00:41:22.239
up.
 

00:41:22.239 --> 00:41:49.780
&lt;&lt;plays music while
student&gt;&gt;

00:41:49.780 --> 00:41:53.376
Okay, so notice there,
how as we come to the end of

00:41:53.376 --> 00:41:57.764
that, we work up there--it rises
up through the rising melodic

00:41:57.764 --> 00:41:58.699
sequence.
 

00:41:58.699 --> 00:42:01.960
We get--Lauren hits that high
note up there,

00:42:01.960 --> 00:42:04.980
and then comes off of
it--that's the climax,

00:42:04.980 --> 00:42:08.210
the peak of the whole aria--
and then the bass,

00:42:08.210 --> 00:42:10.119
what's the bass doing?
 

00:42:10.119 --> 00:42:14.550
 
 

00:42:14.550 --> 00:42:21.119
It's sort of sneaking back down
to the tonic.

00:42:21.119 --> 00:42:26.590
And when we get back to the
tonic, then it comes in.

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:30.320
We're going to pick it up from
there.

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:34.786
Lauren, we're going to sing to
that when we get over there to

00:42:34.786 --> 00:42:36.500
&gt;
 

00:42:36.500 --> 00:42:39.693
just hold on "cor"
and we'll ask them a question:

00:42:39.693 --> 00:42:40.849
What happened here?
 

00:42:40.849 --> 00:42:42.690
What do we have here?
 

00:42:42.690 --> 00:42:45.269
We'll see if you can hold on
that "cor."

00:42:45.269 --> 00:42:48.530
From the "voi."
 

00:42:48.530 --> 00:43:17.550
&lt;&lt;plays piano while
student sings&gt;&gt;

00:43:17.550 --> 00:43:20.760
Prof: Nice.
 

00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:22.980
So what did Mozart do there?
 

00:43:22.980 --> 00:43:23.940
What was that?
 

00:43:23.940 --> 00:43:25.489
Student:  Had a
deceptive cadence.

00:43:25.489 --> 00:43:27.829
Prof: Had a deceptive
cadence--good,

00:43:27.829 --> 00:43:29.280
Marcus scores big today.
 

00:43:29.280 --> 00:43:37.070
We're sitting here on this:
&gt;

00:43:37.070 --> 00:43:41.760
We want it to go:
&gt;

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:47.150
But instead it goes:
&gt;

00:43:47.150 --> 00:43:48.920
That's the "cor."
 

00:43:48.920 --> 00:43:57.664
And then we have our flyover:
&lt;&lt;plays piano while

00:43:57.664 --> 00:44:01.389
